<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-quasiquotation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Quasiquotation</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Now that you understand the tree structure of R code, it's time to
        return to one of the fundamental ideas that make <c>expr()</c> and
        <c>ast()</c> work: quasiquotation. There are two sides to
        quasiquotation:
      </p>

      <p><ul>
        <li><p>
          <em>Quoting</em> allows you to capture an unevaluated expression.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <em>Unquoting</em> allows you to selectively evaluate parts of an
          otherwise quoted expression.
        </p></li>
      </ul></p>

      <p>
        Together, this makes it easy to compose expressions that contain a
        mixture of direct, fixed code, and user-supplied code.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-motivation-quasi">
      <title>Motivation</title>

      <p>
        We'll start with a concrete example that helps motivate the need for
        unquoting, and hence quasiquotation. Imagine you're creating a lot of
        strings by joining together words:
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
paste("Good", "morning", "Hadley")
#&gt; [1] "Good morning Hadley"
paste("Good", "afternoon", "Alice")
#&gt; [1] "Good afternoon Alice"
        </input>
      </program>
    </section>

  </chapter>
